5|$|Born in Mayesville, South Carolina, {{to parents}} who had been slaves, she started working in fields with her family at age five. She took an early {{interest}} in becoming educated; {{with the help of}} benefactors, Bethune attended college hoping to become a missionary in Africa. She started a school <b>for</b> <b>African-American</b> girls in Daytona Beach, Florida. It later merged with a private institute <b>for</b> <b>African-American</b> boys, and was known as the Bethune-Cookman School. Bethune maintained high standards and promoted the school with tourists and donors, to demonstrate what educated African Americans could do. She was president of the college from 1923 to 1942, and 1946 to 1947. She {{was one of the few}} women in the world to serve as a college president at that time.|$|E
